\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Functional Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Class Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
moment 
\series default
is by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Ij$
\end_inset

 is a subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The moment problem says that if we are given a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 of real numbers, can we find a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,1]$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hausdorff moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Stieltjes moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hamburger moment problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us start with some intuition on how we can solve this problem.
 For a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, let us denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle f,\mu\rangle=\int_{I}f\mathrm{d}\mu\label{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In some sense, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 behaves like an inner-product.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 are different types of mathematical objects; one is a function and the
 other is a measure.
 So for all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convex Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
convex 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in S$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propconvexlinearcombinc}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a convex subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\in C$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}t_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}t_{i}x_{i}\in C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i=1}^{n}t_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is minimal in the sense that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i'=1}^{n'}t_{i'}'x_{i'}$
\end_inset

 is another representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, where each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i'}\in S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i'}'\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i'=1}^{n'}t_{i'}'=1$
\end_inset

, then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq n'$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin C$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{t_{i}}{1-t_{n}}((1-t_{n})x_{i}+t_{n}x_{n}) & =\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}t_{i}x_{i}+\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{t_{i}}{1-t_{n}}\right)t_{n}x_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}t_{i}x_{i}+\left(\frac{1-t_{n}}{1-t_{n}}\right)t_{n}x_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}t_{i}x_{i}+t_{n}x_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}t_{i}x_{i}\\
 & =x,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

gives another representation with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 terms, a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Convex Closure and Closed Convex Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
convex closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{conv}(S)=\left\{ tx+(1-t)y\mid t\in(0,1)\text{ and }x,y\in S\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 is a norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 is a normed linear space.
 The 
\series bold
closed convex closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the smallest closed convex set which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With the notation as above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S)$
\end_inset

 is the smallest convex set which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)}=\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S)$
\end_inset

 is in fact a convex set.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t,t'\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,x',y,y'\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(tx+(1-t)y)+(1-s)(t'x'+(1-t')y')=stx+s(1-t)y+(1-s)t'x'+(1-s)(1-t')y'\in\mathrm{conv}(S),
\]

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propconvexlinearcombinc})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 together with the fact that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
st+s(1-t)+(1-s)t'+(1-s)(1-t')=1.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S)$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 It is also the smallest convex set which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 since if 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\in C$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in S$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S)\subseteq C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)}=\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, first note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

 is convex, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S)\subseteq\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

, and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)} & \subseteq\overline{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)}\\
 & =\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For the reverse inclusion, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)}$
\end_inset

 is convex, since then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)}$
\end_inset

 would be a closed convex set, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)\subseteq\overline{\mathrm{conv}(S)}$
\end_inset

 by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we will show that the closure of a convex set is convex.
 To this end, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\overline{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\to y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(tx_{n}+(1-t)y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex) which converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\in\overline{C}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{C}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Convex Closure Preserves Minkowski Sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1},S_{2}$
\end_inset

 be subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
Minkowski sum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}+S_{2}=\{x_{1}+x_{2}\mid x_{1}\in S_{1}\text{ and }x_{2}\in S_{2}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},C_{2}$
\end_inset

 be convex subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}+C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{1}'\in C_{1}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2},c_{2}'\in C_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t(c_{1}+c_{2})+(1-t)(c_{1}'+c_{2}')=(tc_{1}+(1-t)c_{1}')+(tc_{2}+(1-t)c_{2}')\in C_{1}+C_{2},
\]

\end_inset

since both 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 are convex.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}+C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1},S_{2}$
\end_inset

 be subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{conv}(S_{1}+S_{2})=\mathrm{conv}(S_{1})+\mathrm{conv}(S_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{conv}(S_{1})+\mathrm{conv}(S_{2})$
\end_inset

 is a convex set which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}+S_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{conv}(S_{1}+S_{2})\subseteq\mathrm{conv}(S_{1})+\mathrm{conv}(S_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}\in\mathrm{conv}(S_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}\in\mathrm{conv}(S_{2})$
\end_inset

 and express them as 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}=t_{1}x_{1}+(1-t_{1})y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}=t_{2}x_{2}+(1-t_{1})y_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},y_{1}\in S_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2},y_{2}\in S_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z_{1}+z_{2} & =t_{1}x_{1}+(1-t_{1})y_{1}+t_{2}x_{2}+(1-t_{2})y_{2}\\
 & =t_{1}x_{1}+t_{2}x_{2}+y_{1}-t_{1}y_{1}+y_{2}-t_{2}y_{2}\\
 & =(t_{1}-t_{2})(x_{1}+y_{2})+t_{2}(x_{1}+x_{2})+(1-t_{1})(y_{1}+y_{2}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{1}-t_{2})+t_{2}+(1-t_{1})=1$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}+y_{2},x_{1}+x_{2},y_{1}+y_{2}\in S_{1}+S_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}+z_{2}\in\mathrm{conv}(S_{1}+S_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have the reverse inclusion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{conv}(S_{1}+S_{2})\supseteq\mathrm{conv}(S_{1})+\mathrm{conv}(S_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convex Cones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $P\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
convex cone 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in P$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in P$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x\in P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given a convex cone 
\begin_inset Formula $P\subseteq V$
\end_inset

, we can define a partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq_{P}y$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x\in P$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this is a preorder, note that reflexivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in P$
\end_inset

.
 Transitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq_{P}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq_{P}z$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $z-x=(z-y)+(y-x)\in P$
\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq_{P}z$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}$
\end_inset

 is in fact a preorder.
 If we assume in addition that 
\begin_inset Formula $-P\cap P=0$
\end_inset

, then we also have antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}.$
\end_inset

 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}$
\end_inset

 is a partial order.
 Note that, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq_{P}x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

, thus it makes sense to call the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
positive 
\series default
elements with respect to the preorder 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Marcel Riesz Extension Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Marcel Riesz Extension Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $P\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex cone.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W+P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi|_{P\cap W}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{P}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V\backslash W$
\end_inset

.
 We will first show that we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 preserves the positivity condition.
 Define two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{x\in W\mid-x\leq_{P}v\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{y\in W\mid v\leq_{P}y\}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W+P$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}\leq\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}.\label{eq:convexconeineq-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $-x\leq_{P}v\leq_{P}y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in C$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\psi(x+y)\\
 & =\psi(x)+\psi(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\psi(x)\leq\psi(y)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:convexconeineq-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(v)$
\end_inset

 to be any number between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}$
\end_inset

 and we define we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v)=\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\label{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in W+\mathbb{R}v$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\psi(x)\leq\widetilde{\psi}(v)\leq\psi(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 The only thing left is to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the positivity condition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in P\cap(W+\mathbb{R}v)$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the following cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\lambda)w+v=(1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in P$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\lambda)w\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\lambda(\psi((1/\lambda)w)+\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\series bold
Case 2: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1/\lambda)w-v=(-1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in P$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1/\lambda)w\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq-\lambda(\psi((-1/\lambda)w)-\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 3: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in P\cap W$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\psi(w)=\widetilde{\psi}(w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all three cases, we see that the positivity condition is satisfied.
 Thus we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to a linear functional on 
\begin_inset Formula $W+\mathbb{R}v$
\end_inset

 while preserving the positivity condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we must appeal to Zorn's Lemma.
 More specifically, we define a partially ordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 as follows: the underlying set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}=\{\text{linear functionals }\psi'\colon W'\to\mathbb{R}\mid W'\supseteq W,\text{ }\psi'|_{W}=\psi\text{, and }\psi'|_{W'\cap C=P}\geq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

A member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by an ordered pair: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 are two members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})\leq(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}\subseteq W_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}|_{W_{1}}=\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that every totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 Then if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $W'=\bigcup_{i\in I}W_{i}$
\end_inset

 and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'(x)=\psi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

 is a member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and that it is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty (it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi,W)$
\end_inset

) and every totally ordered subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound, we can apply Zorn's Lemma to obtain a 
\emph on
maximal 
\emph default
element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 This maximal element 
\emph on
must 
\emph default
be defined on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, otherwise we can extend it to a larger subspace as shown above and obtain
 a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hausdorff Moment Problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=P[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{\text{nonnegative continuous functions on }[0,1]\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 we write it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=b_{n}x^{n}+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}x+b_{0},
\]

\end_inset

and we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(p)=b_{n}a_{n}+b_{n-1}a_{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}a_{1}+b_{0}a_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i})=a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This is clearly a linear functional on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The first crucial step is to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We'll need to use the following theorem of Bernstein:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (S.
 Bernstein) A polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is non-negative on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 if and only if it can be represented as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=A_{0}x^{n}+A_{1}x^{n-1}(1-x)+A_{2}x^{n-2}(1-x)^{2}+\cdots+A_{n-1}x(1-x)^{n-1}+A_{n}(1-x)^{n}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1},\dots,A_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 then by the previous theorem of Bernstein, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that this is a sufficient condition too.
 We write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{i}(1-x)^{j}=x^{i}\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{k}=\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{i+k}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j}) & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}\psi(x^{i+k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we need to impose the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Under this condition, we have that all conditions of the Marcel Riesz extension
 theorem are satisfied, namely we need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{P}+\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 However this is clear: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bounded, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-M)+M,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-M\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So applying the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathcal{M}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(p)=\psi(p)$
\end_inset

 for any polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The final important ingredient is the Riesz Representation Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riesz Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmadinnistheorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Dini's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n}\colon X\to\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be an increasing sequence of continuous functions which converges pointwise
 to a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}=f-f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}=\{g_{n}<\varepsilon\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and thus each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is increasing, each 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{n})$
\end_inset

 is decreasing, and thus the sequence of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, it follows that the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By compactness of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can choose a finite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending, this means that there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{N}=X$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing such an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varepsilon & >g_{n}(x)\\
 & =f(x)-f_{n}(x)\\
 & =|f(x)-f_{n}(x)|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a unique finite (positive) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Uniqueness is clear.
 Let's prove existence.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all bounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all nonnegative bounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $B[0,1]$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 as subspace and it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $B[0,1]=C[0,1]+N[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for any bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in B[0,1]$
\end_inset

 there exists a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\leq f$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-g)+g
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in N[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $N[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone and by assumption we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]\cap N[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 So by the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists a linear functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\colon B[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{C[0,1]}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{N[0,1]}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now we define a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(E)=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{E})
\]

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We next show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a measure.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of pairwise disjoint sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}-f,f-f_{n}\leq|f_{n}-f|\leq\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}
\]

\end_inset

 By the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f),\widetilde{\ell}(f-f_{n})\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f)|\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}})=\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}\widetilde{\ell}(1).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the sup norm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly (Dini's Theorem).
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is increasing and converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}})$
\end_inset

 is increasing and converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{n=1}^{N}1_{E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\widetilde{\ell}(E_{n})\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\mu(E_{n})\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(E_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a Borel measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 It is finite since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu([0,1])=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{[0,1]})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an increasing sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n})$
\end_inset

 of simple functions which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then by MCT we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi\mathrm{d}\mu & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\mu(A_{k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\widetilde{\ell}(1_{A_{k}})\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}\right)\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\ell(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\ell(f)
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\int f\mathrm{d}\mu$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another formulation of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) For any bounded (with respect to the supremum
 norm) linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique finite (signed) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And a more general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Kakutani general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact Hausdorff topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 be the Banach space of all continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the supremum norm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|f\|_{\infty}=\sup_{x\in X}|f(x)|.
\]

\end_inset

For any bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C(X)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique Borel regular measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly continuous.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 define a partition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0<x_{0}^{(n)}<x_{1}^{(n)}<\cdots<x_{n}^{(n)}=1
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that none of these points are discontinuities of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x_{i+1}^{(n)}-x_{i}^{(n)}|<\frac{2}{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{n}(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly continuous, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu$
\end_inset

.
 So it suffices to show
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu=\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n}) & =\widetilde{\ell}(\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]})\\
 & =\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})\widetilde{\ell}(1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]})\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hausdorff) A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a moment sequence of some finite Borel measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}x^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset

if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{k}(\Delta^{k}a)_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k,n\geq0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Delta a)_{n}=a_{n+1}-a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta^{2}a & =\Delta(\Delta a)\\
 & =(a_{n+2}-2a_{n+1}+a_{n})_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

More generally
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta^{k}a=(\sum_{i=n}^{n+k}(-1)^{i}{n \choose i}a_{n+i}).
\]

\end_inset

Sequences satisfying this condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((-1)^{k}\Delta^{k}a)_{n}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

are called monotone sequences.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-1)^{k}(\Delta^{k}a)_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}x^{n}(1-x)^{k}\mathrm{d}\mu\geq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hahn-Banach Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 A 
\series bold
partial-seminorm 
\series default
is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(nonnegativity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(nonnegative homogeneity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\lambda x)=\lambda p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x+y)\leq p(x)+p(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The terminology 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial-seminorm
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is made up by me.
 Recall that a 
\series bold
seminorm 
\series default
is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(absolute homogeneity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\lambda x)=|\lambda|p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x+y)\leq p(x)+p(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to check that a seminorm is necessarily nonnegative.
 Thus every seminorm is a partial-seminorm.
 On the other hand, there are partial-seminorms which are not seminorms.
 Indeed, consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=\begin{cases}
x & \text{if }x\geq0\\
-x/2 & \text{if }x<0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm which is not a seminorm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space equipped with a partial-seminorm 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then every linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}|_{U}=\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\widetilde{\varphi}|\leq p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that by 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

, we mean 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi(u)|\leq p(u)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 We will construct an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 using Marcel Riesz's Extension Theorem.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\{(\lambda,v)\in\mathbb{R}\times V\mid p(v)\leq\lambda\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone contained in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times V$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha\lambda,\alpha v)\in P$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha v) & =\alpha p(v)\\
 & \leq\alpha\lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{1},v_{1}),(\lambda_{2},v_{2})\in P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2},v_{1}+v_{2})\in P$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(v_{1}+v_{2}) & \leq p(v_{1})+p(v_{2})\\
 & =\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times V=(\mathbb{R}\times U)+P$
\end_inset

 , since if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in\mathbb{R}\times V$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\lambda,v)=(\lambda-p(v),0)+(p(v),v)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda-p(v),0)\in\mathbb{R}\times U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p(v),v)\in P$
\end_inset

.
 Finally define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathbb{R}\times U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\lambda,u)=\lambda-\varphi(u)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,u)\in\mathbb{R}\times U$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi|_{(\mathbb{R}\times U)\cap P}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in(\mathbb{R}\times U)\cap P$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(\lambda,v) & =\lambda-\varphi(v)\\
 & \geq\lambda-p(v)\\
 & \geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we have all of the ingredients to apply the Marcel Riesz Extension
 Theorem: choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathbb{R}\times V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{\mathbb{R}\times U}=\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{P}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}(v)=-\widetilde{\psi}(0,v)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}(u) & =-\widetilde{\psi}(0,u)\\
 & =-\psi(0,u)\\
 & =\varphi(u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}|_{U}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We claim 
\begin_inset Formula $|\widetilde{\varphi}|\leq p$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}(v_{0})>p(v_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then using that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p(x_{0}),x_{0})\in P$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\widetilde{\psi}(p(x_{0}),x_{0})\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(0,x_{0})+\widetilde{\psi}(p(x_{0}),0)\\
 & =-\widetilde{\varphi}(x_{0})+\psi(p(x_{0}),0)\\
 & =-\widetilde{\varphi}(x_{0})+p(x_{0})\\
 & <-p(x_{0})+p(x_{0})\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a contradiction.
 This establishes our claim and we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the setting of normed linear spaces, the Hahn-Banach Theorem says that
 any linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 defined on a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 which is bounded on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{Y}}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\widetilde{\ell}\|_{\mathcal{X}}=\|\ell\|_{\mathcal{Y}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is an immediate consequence of our more general version that we have
 just proved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\ell\|=1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{0})=\|x_{0}\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So if you have two points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a)\neq\ell(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a reflexive Banach space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,\mathcal{Y})=\|x-y_{0}\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 with a convex set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{Y}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(y)=\|y-x\|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Geometric Form of the Hahn-Banach Theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauge Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defninteriorpoint}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 is said to be an 
\series bold
internal point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+ty\in S$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all points internal points of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
core 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{core}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us make several remarks about this definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 to emphasize that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
depends 
\emph default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Usually we will just write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{core}\,S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{core}\,S$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0,0}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon_{0,0}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0+t\cdot0\in S$
\end_inset

.
 The converse of course isn't true (take 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{0\}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is equipped with a metric.
 Recall that a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 is said to be an 
\series bold
interior point
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}(x)\subseteq S$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all interior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that every interior point of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an internal point of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,S\subseteq\mathrm{core}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 happens to be open, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{int}\,S\subseteq\mathrm{core}\,S=S$
\end_inset

 which forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,S=\mathrm{core}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an internal point.
 We define the 
\series bold
gauge functional 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to be the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)=\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)x\in C\}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 be an internal point of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 guarantees that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is an internal point, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $tx\in C$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1/\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\alpha<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\leq1/\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus having 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 be an internal point of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 guarantees that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}(x)=\|x\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gauge Functional is a Partial-Seminorm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propgaugefunctionalisquasiseminorm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an internal point.
 Then the gauge functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is subadditive.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)+\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/a)x,(1/b)x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{a+b}(x+y)=\frac{a}{a+b}\left(\frac{1}{a}x\right)+\frac{b}{a+b}\left(\frac{1}{b}y\right)\in C.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)+\varepsilon & =a+b\\
 & \geq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x+y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is subadditive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 satisfies nonnegative homogeneity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 First note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

, then since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(0) & =\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)\cdot0\in C\}=0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0\cdot\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)=\mathrm{p}_{C}(0\cdot x)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(\lambda x) & =\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)\lambda x\in C\}\\
 & =\lambda\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)x\in C\}\\
 & =\lambda\mathrm{p}_{C}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Finally note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative by definition.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Properties of Gauge Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an internal point.
 We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\mathrm{p}_{C}\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{core}\,C=\{\mathrm{p}_{C}<1\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/1)x\in C$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{core}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\varepsilon x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+\varepsilon x & =(1+\varepsilon)x\\
 & =\frac{1}{1/(1+\varepsilon)}x
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\leq1/(1+\varepsilon)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha<1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{core}(C)$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ty\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+(1-\alpha)ty & =\alpha(1/\alpha)x+(1-\alpha)ty\in C
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 In particular, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=(1-\alpha)\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+ty\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gauge Functional Induced from Partial-Seminorm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propgaugefunctionalisquasiseminorm})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex subset of a real vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{core}\,C$
\end_inset

, then the gauge functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 We will now show a converse to this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a partial-seminorm, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{p\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set, and moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p((1-\alpha)x+\alpha y) & \leq p((1-\alpha)x)+p(\alpha y)\\
 & =(1-\alpha)p(x)+\alpha p(y)\\
 & \leq(1-\alpha)+\alpha\\
 & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\alpha)x+\alpha y\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})<p(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})\leq\alpha<p(x_{0})
\]

\end_inset

and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p((1/\alpha)x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)p(x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{0})\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\geq p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{0})<\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x_{0})\leq\alpha<\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)p(x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $p((1/\alpha)x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the infimum of all such 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\geq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty convex subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{core}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin C$
\end_inset

, there exists a hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is some linear functional and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By translating if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 This means it is possible to define the gauge potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathbb{R}y\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(ay)=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $ay\in\mathbb{R}y$
\end_inset

.
 Notice if 
\begin_inset Formula $a<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(ay) & =a\\
 & <0\\
 & \leq\mathrm{p}_{C}(ay),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(ay) & =a\\
 & \leq a\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)\\
 & =\mathrm{p}_{C}(ay),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)\geq1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin\mathrm{core}\,C=C$
\end_inset

.
 So we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}|_{\mathbb{R}y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore by the Hahn-Banach Theorem, we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathbb{R}y}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(x)\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\widetilde{\ell}<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
 Also clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(y)=1$
\end_inset

, and so we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First Geometric Form of Hahn-Banach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (first geometric form of Hahn-Banach) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be nonempty convex sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathrm{core}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a hyperplane that separates 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, there exists a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell\geq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=A-B=\{a-b\mid a\in A,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty convex set.
 Furthermore we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,C=C$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b\in C$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a+ty\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b+ty=(a+ty)-b\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Finally note that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin C$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint from one another.
 By the previous result, there exists a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\{\ell=\beta\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\ell<\beta\}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(0)=\beta$
\end_inset

, we must necessarily have 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b\in C$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0>\ell(a-b)=\ell(a)-\ell(b)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a)<\ell(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}\leq\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}.
\]

\end_inset

So choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell\geq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second Geometric Form of Hahn-Banach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaclosed+compact=closed}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a compact subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{A+B}$
\end_inset

 and choose a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n}+b_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}+b_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exist a convergent subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{n})$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{\pi(n)})$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, by relabeling indices if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{n})$
\end_inset

 is convergent, say 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\to b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}+b_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\to b$
\end_inset

, it follows easily that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\to x-b$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x-b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x-b)+b$
\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A+B$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=\overline{A+B}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is closed.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (second geometric form of Hahn-Banach) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be two nonempty convex sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Then there exists a closed hyperplane that strictly separates 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=A-B=\{a-b\mid a\in A,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty convex set.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is closed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaclosed+compact=closed})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $-B$
\end_inset

 is compact and 
\begin_inset Formula $A-B=A+(-B)$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin C$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint from one another.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}$
\end_inset

 is open and contains 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, which means there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq C^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\cap C=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 By the previous first geometric form of Hahn-Banach, we can separate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 by a hyperplane, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a-b)\leq\ell(rx)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 It can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(a-b)\leq\inf\{\ell(rx)\mid x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)\}=-r\|\ell\|.
\]

\end_inset

Now take 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=(1/2)r\|\ell\|>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(a)+\varepsilon\leq\ell(b)-\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}<\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}.
\]

\end_inset

So choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 strictly between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lower Semicontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
lower semicontinuous 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi\leq c\}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some basic facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 is a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are lower semicontinuous implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}+\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of lower semicontinuous functions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{i\in I}\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is also lower semicontinuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is compact, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf_{x\in\mathcal{K}}\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 is acheived.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convexity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
convex 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(tx+(1-t)y)\leq t\varphi(x)+(1-t)\varphi(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some basic facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is convex if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 is a convex set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}+\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 are all convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{i\in I}\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi\leq c\}$
\end_inset

 is a convex set for all 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The converse is not true in general.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We usually assume both convexity and lower semicontinuity in optimization
 problems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conjugate Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be a function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define the 
\series bold
conjugate function 
\series default
of
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be the function
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\colon\mathcal{X}^{*}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)=\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi(x))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The conjugate function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is sometimes called a 
\series bold
Fenchel transform 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 or a 
\series bold
Legendre transform 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define the 
\series bold
double conjugate function 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to be the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{**}(x)=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=\frac{1}{p}|x|^{p}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1<p<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Recall from the Riesz representation theorem for Hilbert, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\ell_{y}$
\end_inset

 for a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{y}(x)=yx$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Using this fact, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\ell_{y}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(y) & :=\varphi^{*}(\ell_{y})\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathbb{R}}(\ell_{y}(x)-\varphi(x))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathbb{R}}\left(yx-\frac{1}{p}|x|^{p}\right)\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathbb{R}}\left(|y||x|-\frac{1}{p}|x|^{p}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{q}|y|^{q}+\frac{1}{p}|y^{p/q}|^{p}-\frac{1}{p}|y^{p/q}|^{p}\\
 & =\frac{1}{q}|y|^{q},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1<q<\infty$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/p+1/q=1$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we used Young's inequality, which says
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{a^{p}}{p}+\frac{b^{q}}{q}\geq ab
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\geq0$
\end_inset

, with equality acheived if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=b^{q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The example above suggests that we have the following generalization of
 Young's inequality: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)+\varphi(x)\geq\ell(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this is a simple consequence of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi(x))\\
 & \geq\varphi(x)-\ell(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fenchel-Moreau
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaconjugatenotinfty}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be a lower semicontinuous convex function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}<\varphi(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the normed linear space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and the subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(x_{0},\lambda_{0})\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty closed convex set and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty compact convex set.
 Furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint from one another.
 Thus by the second geometric form of Hahn-Banach, there exists a bounded
 linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}\quad\text{and}\quad B\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}.\label{eq:strictsepnotinfty}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\ell(x,0)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear functional because 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear functional and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=\ell|_{\mathbb{R}\times\{0\}}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\ell(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x,\lambda) & =\ell(x,0)+\ell(0,\lambda)\\
 & =\psi(x)+\lambda k
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\lambda)\in\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:strictsepnotinfty})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
\psi(x)+\lambda k>\alpha & \text{if }(x,\lambda)\in A\\
\psi(x_{0})+\lambda_{0}k<\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},\varphi(x_{0}))\in A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & <\psi(x_{0})+\varphi(x_{0})k-\alpha\\
 & <\psi(x_{0})+\varphi(x_{0})k-\psi(x_{0})-\lambda_{0}k\\
 & =\varphi(x_{0})k-\lambda_{0}k\\
 & =(\varphi(x_{0})-\lambda_{0})k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0})>\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\varphi(x))\in A$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, we can divide 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)+\lambda k>\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/k$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{1}{k}\psi(x)-\varphi(x)<-\frac{\alpha}{k}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(-\psi/k) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(-\psi(x)/k-\varphi(x))\\
 & \leq-\frac{\alpha}{k}\\
 & <\infty.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Fenchel-Moreau) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon X\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous, convex, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\ell(x)-\sup_{y\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(y)-\varphi(y))\\
 & \leq\ell(x)-(\ell(x)-\varphi(x))\\
 & =\varphi(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell))\\
 & \leq\varphi(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}(x)\geq\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1: 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\geq0$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}(x_{0})<\varphi(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 We apply the second geometric form of Hahn-Banach again in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\le\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(x_{0},\varphi^{**}(x_{0}))\}$
\end_inset

.
 By the same argument as in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconjugatenotinfty})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(x)+\lambda k>\alpha\label{eq:firstineqfen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\lambda)\in A$
\end_inset

 and such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(x_{0})+k\varphi^{**}(x_{0})<\alpha\label{eq:secondineqfen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that we could have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0})=\infty$
\end_inset

, so we can't plug in 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},\varphi(x_{0}))$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:firstineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 as in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconjugatenotinfty})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 However we can still show that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{0},\varphi(y_{0}))\in A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(y_{0})+k\lambda\geq\ell(y_{0})+k\varphi(y_{0})>\alpha
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq\varphi(y_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty\geq\alpha$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 So we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 In order to proceed with the proof, we need to make 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 a little bigger, so choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $k+\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then just as in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconjugatenotinfty})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell\right)=\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell(x)-\varphi(x)\right)\leq-\frac{\alpha}{k+\varepsilon}
\]

\end_inset

and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x_{0})+(k+\varepsilon)\varphi^{**}(x_{0}) & =\ell(x_{0})+(k+\varepsilon)\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x_{0})-\varphi^{*}(\ell))\\
 & \geq\ell(x_{0})+(k+\varepsilon)\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell(x_{0})-\varphi^{*}\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell\right)\right)\\
 & \geq\ell(x_{0})+(k+\varepsilon)\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell(x_{0})+\frac{\alpha}{k+\varepsilon}\right)\\
 & =\ell(x_{0})-\ell(x_{0})+\alpha\\
 & =\alpha.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(x_{0})+k\varphi^{**}(x_{0})\geq\alpha,
\]

\end_inset

which contradicts 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:secondineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This contradiction proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}\geq\varphi$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
Now consider the general case where we may not have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

 (such 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}$
\end_inset

 exists by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconjugatenotinfty})
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(x)=\varphi(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex, lower semicontinuous, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 So by step 1, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}^{**}=\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi_{1}(x))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi(x)+\ell_{0}(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}((\ell+\ell_{0})(x)-\varphi(x))-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0})\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi_{1}^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell+\ell_{0}\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}((\ell+\ell_{0})(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\varphi^{**}(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{**}(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}) & =\varphi_{1}^{**}(x)\\
 & =\varphi_{1}(x)\\
 & =\varphi(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and consider let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 be the norm function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous and convex.
 Let's compute the conjugate function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\|x\|)\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}\|x\|\left(\ell\left(\frac{x}{\|x\|}\right)-1\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\ell\|>1$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x_{0}\|=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{0})>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}\|x\|\left(\ell\left(\frac{x}{\|x\|}\right)-1\right)\\
 & \geq\|\lambda x_{0}\|\left(\ell\left(\frac{\lambda x_{0}}{\|\lambda x_{0}\|}\right)-1\right)\\
 & =|\lambda|\left(\ell(x_{0})-1\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\ell)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\ell\|\leq1$
\end_inset

, then it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\ell)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }\|\ell\|\leq1\\
\infty & \text{if }\|\ell\|>1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

For a set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 nonempty we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}_{E}(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }x\in E\\
\infty & \text{if }x\notin E
\end{cases}=\log\left(\frac{1}{1_{E}(x)}\right)
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}=1_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]=\{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\mid\|\ell\|\leq1\}.
\]

\end_inset

Now we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|x\| & =\varphi(x)\\
 & =\varphi^{**}(x)\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(x))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}(x))\\
 & =\sup_{\substack{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\\
\|\ell\|\leq1
}
}\ell(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This identity can be proved in a more elementary way by applying Hahn-Banach.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Support Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}\colon\mathcal{X}^{*}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell)=\sup_{x\in S}\ell(x).
\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
support functional 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Basic Properties of Support Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}=\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{conv}(S)}=\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 be subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}=\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{K}}(\ell)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }\ell\in\mathcal{K}^{\perp}\\
\infty & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\perp}=\{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\mid\ell|_{\mathcal{K}}=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(0)=0$
\end_inset

 for all linear functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{q}_{S}(\lambda\ell) & =\sup_{x\in S}\ell(\lambda x)\\
 & =\sup_{x\in S}\lambda\ell(x)\\
 & =\lambda\sup_{x\in S}\ell(x)\\
 & =\lambda\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1},\ell_{2}\in\mathcal{X}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell_{1}+\ell_{2}) & =\sup_{x\in S}\{(\ell_{1}+\ell_{2})(x)\}\\
 & =\sup_{x\in S}\{\ell_{1}(x)+\ell_{2}(x)\}\\
 & \leq\sup_{x\in S}\{\ell_{1}(x)\}+\sup_{x\in S}\{\ell_{2}(x)\}\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell_{1})+\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq\mathrm{conv}(S)\subseteq\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)$
\end_inset

, we clearly have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S}\leq\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{conv}(S)}\leq\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\in\mathrm{conv}(S)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(tx+(1-t)y) & =t\ell(x)+(1-t)\ell(y)\\
 & \leq t\sup_{z\in S}\ell(z)+(1-t)\sup_{z\in S}\ell(z)\\
 & =t\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell)+(1-t)\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell)\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{conv}(S)}(\ell)\leq\mathrm{q}_{S}(\ell)$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{conv}(S)}\leq\mathrm{q}_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(S)}\leq\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{conv}(S)}$
\end_inset

, we will prove something more general: if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\overline{E}}\leq\mathrm{q}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{E}$
\end_inset

, and choose a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x) & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\ell(x_{n})\\
 & \leq\sup_{y\in E}\ell(y)\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\overline{E}}(\ell)\leq\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\overline{E}}\leq\mathrm{q}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}+x_{2}\in S_{1}+S_{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x_{1}+x_{2}) & =\ell(x_{1})+\ell(x_{2})\\
 & \leq\sup_{y_{1}\in S_{1}}\ell(y_{1})+\sup_{y_{2}\in S_{2}}\ell(y_{2})\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}(\ell)+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}(\ell)\\
 & =(\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}})(\ell)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}(\ell)\leq(\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}})(\ell)$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}\leq\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\in S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\in S_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{1})+\varepsilon/2>\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{2})+\varepsilon/2>\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}(\ell)$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}})(\ell) & =\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}(\ell)+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}(\ell)\\
 & <\ell(x_{1})+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\ell(x_{2})+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\\
 & =\ell(x_{1})+\ell(x_{2})+\varepsilon\\
 & =\ell(x_{1}+x_{2})+\varepsilon\\
 & \leq\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}(\ell)+\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}})(\ell)\leq\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}(\ell)$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}}+\mathrm{q}_{S_{2}}\leq\mathrm{q}_{S_{1}+S_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 First suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{K}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{K}}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{K}}\ell(x)\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{K}}0\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\notin\mathcal{K}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\ell(x) & =\ell(\lambda x)\\
 & \leq\sup_{y\in\mathcal{K}}\ell(y)\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{K}}(\ell).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{K}}(\ell)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of Support Functionals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{x_{0}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\{x_{0}\}}(\ell)=\ell(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}=\|\ell\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{B}_{R}[0]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{B}_{R}[0]}=R\|\ell\|$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that the gauge functional in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{\mathrm{B}_{R}[0]}(x)=\|x\|/R$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{B}_{R}[x_{0}]}(x) & =\mathrm{q}_{\{x_{0}\}+\mathrm{B}_{R}[0]}(x)\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{\{x_{0}\}}(x)+\mathrm{q}_{\mathrm{B}_{R}[0]}(x)\\
 & =\ell(x_{0})+R\|\ell\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{M}}(\ell)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }\ell\in\mathcal{M}^{\perp}\\
\infty & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\mathrm{I}_{E}(x)$
\end_inset

 for some set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{E}(x))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in E}\ell(x)\\
 & =\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Notice 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\ell)=\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}(\ell)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}(\ell))
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{E}$
\end_inset

 is convex if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 It can also be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{E}$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is clsoed and convex, then Fenchel-Moreau applies and we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}_{E}(x)=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some sense, the gauge (Minkowski) functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 plays the role of a norm if we want 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 convex to play the role of the unit ball.
 In that sense, the support functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{C}$
\end_inset

 plays the role of the norm in the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 In this direct, the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $|\ell(x)|\leq\|\ell\|\|x\|$
\end_inset

 is replaced by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|\ell(x)|\leq\mathrm{q}_{C}(\ell)\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\label{eq:cauchyschwarzgen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x/(\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\varepsilon)\in C$
\end_inset

 by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)$
\end_inset

, and thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell\left(\frac{1}{\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\varepsilon}x\right)\leq\sup_{y\in C}\ell(y)=\mathrm{q}_{C}(\ell)
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:cauchyschwarzgen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)\leq\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{E}^{*}(\ell)=\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)=\mathrm{q}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}(\ell)=\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}_{E}^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{E}^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

On the other hand, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}_{E}^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}^{**}(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can apply Fenchel-Moreau to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}$
\end_inset

 which is convex and lowersemicontinuous and obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell))
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\in\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E) & \iff\mathrm{I}_{\overline{\mathrm{conv}}(E)}(x)=0\\
 & \iff\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell))=0\\
 & \iff\ell(x)\leq\mathrm{q}_{E}(\ell)\text{ for all }\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Another Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, we define its 
\series bold
annihilator
\series default
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{M}^{\perp}=\{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\mid\ell|_{\mathcal{M}}=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

For a closed subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}\subseteq\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{N}_{\perp}=\{x\in\mathcal{X}\mid\ell(x)=0\text{ for all }\ell\in\mathcal{N}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{M}^{\perp})_{\perp}=\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}}^{*}(\ell)=\mathrm{q}_{\mathcal{M}}(\ell)=\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}^{\perp}}(\ell)$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}}(x) & =\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}}^{**}(x)\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}}^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}^{\perp}}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{M}^{\perp}}(\ell(x))\\
 & =\mathrm{I}_{(\mathcal{M}^{\perp})_{\perp}}(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fenchel-Rockafeller
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Fenchel-Rockafellar) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be two convex functions.
 Suppose there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0}),\psi(x_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\varphi(x)+\psi(x))=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(-\varphi^{*}(-\ell)-\psi^{*}(\ell))=\max_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(-\varphi^{*}(-\ell)-\psi^{*}(\ell)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sketch) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\inf_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\varphi(x)+\psi(x))$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(-\varphi^{*}(-\ell)-\psi^{*}(\ell))$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\leq a$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\varphi^{*}(\ell)-\psi^{*}(\ell) & =-\varphi^{*}(-\ell)-(-\ell(x))-\psi^{*}(\ell)-\ell(x)\\
 & \leq\varphi(x)+\psi(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{epi}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\lambda\leq a-\psi(x)\}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are both nonempty convex sets.
 Furthemore we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (otherwise we'll have 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\lambda)\in\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)<\lambda\leq a-\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)+\psi(x)<a$
\end_inset

, giving a contradiction).
 Applying Hahn-Banach, we obtain a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\colon\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{C}=\overline{A}\subseteq\{\Phi\geq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\Phi\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=\Phi(x,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\Phi(0,1)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x)+k\lambda\geq\alpha & \text{ for }(x,\lambda)\in\overline{A}=\overline{C}\\
\ell(x)+k\lambda\leq\alpha & \text{ for }(x,\lambda)\in B.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly as before, one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty and convex.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{0},C)=\inf_{x\in C}\|x_{0}-x\|=\sup_{\substack{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\\
\|\ell\|\leq1
}
}(\ell(x_{0})-\mathrm{q}_{C}(\ell)).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\|x-x_{0}\|$
\end_inset

 is convex and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\mathrm{I}_{C}(x)$
\end_inset

 is convex if 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\|x-x_{0}\|))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x-x_{0})-\|x-x_{0}\|+\ell(x_{0}))\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\ell)\\
 & =\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}(\ell)+\ell(x_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So by Fenchel-Rockafellar, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\|x-x_{0}\|+\mathrm{I}_{C}(x))=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x_{0})-\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}(-\ell)-\mathrm{q}_{C}(\ell))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before starting the proof, recall that we proved last time using Fenchel-Rockafe
llar that if 
\begin_inset Formula $C\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is convex, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{0},C)=\sup_{\substack{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\\
\|\ell\|\leq1
}
}(\ell(x_{0})-\mathrm{q}_{C}(\ell)).
\]

\end_inset

Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x_{0},C)=\sup_{\substack{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}\\
\|\ell\|\leq1
}
}(\ell(x_{0})-\mathrm{I}_{\mathcal{M}^{\perp}}(\ell))=\sup_{\substack{\ell\in\mathcal{M}^{\perp}\\
\|\ell\|\leq1
}
}\ell(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Baire Category Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a Banach space.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 cannot be represented as a countable union of nowhere dense sets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is said to be nowhere dense if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\overline{E})^{\circ}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 doesn't contain any open balls.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}$
\end_inset

 with every 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 being nowhere dense.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}\overline{E}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{1}}(x_{1})\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be any open ball.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 is nowhere dense, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{1}}(x_{1})\cap\overline{E}_{1}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open set.
 Thus there exists an open ball, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{2}}(x_{2})$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{2}}[x_{2}]\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r_{1}}(x_{1})\cap\overline{E}_{1}^{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}<2^{-2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 is nowhere dense, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{2}}(x_{2})\cap\overline{E}_{2}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open set.
 So by the same reason as before, there exists an open ball, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{3}}(x_{3})$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r_{3}}[x_{3}]\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r_{2}}(x_{2})\cap\overline{E}_{2}^{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{3}<2^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing this process, we obtain a descending sequence of open balls
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{B}_{r_{n}}(x_{n}))$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{r_{n}}[x_{n}]\subseteq\mathrm{B}_{r_{n-1}}(x_{n-1})\cap\overline{E}_{n-1}^{c}\quad\text{and}\quad r_{n}<2^{-n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-N}<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n>m\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|x_{m}-x_{n}\| & \leq r_{m}\\
 & <2^{-m}\\
 & \leq2^{-N}\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence.
 Being a Cauchy sequence in a Banach space, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is convergent, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\mathrm{B}_{r_{k}}(x_{k})$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq k$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{r_{k}}[x_{k}]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & \in\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathrm{B}_{r_{n}}[x_{n}]\\
 & \subseteq\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\overline{E}_{n}^{c}\\
 & =\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}\overline{E}_{n}\right)^{c}\\
 & =\mathcal{X}^{c}\\
 & =\emptyset,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uniform Boundedness Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Uniform Boundedness Principle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be two Banach spaces.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$
\end_inset

 the set of all bounded linear operators from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{L}(X,\mathcal{Y})$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\|Tx\|\mid T\in\mathcal{A}\}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above.
 Then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\|T\|\mid T\in\mathcal{A}\}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{n}=\{x\in\mathcal{X}\mid\|Tx\|\leq n\text{ for all }T\in\mathcal{A}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ascending sequence of closed sets.
 Indeed, it is clearly ascending.
 To see that each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is closed, view it as an infinite intersection of closed sets, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{n}=\bigcap_{T\in\mathcal{A}}\{x\in\mathcal{X}\mid\|Tx\|\leq n\}.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\|Tx\|\mid T\in\mathcal{A}\}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\|Tx\|\mid T\in\mathcal{A}\}\leq N$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E_{N}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{X}=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

By the Baire Category Theorem, there must exist some 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{M}$
\end_inset

 is not nowhere dense.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{M}$
\end_inset

 contains a nonempty contains a nonempty open ball, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 By choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 small enough, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}[x_{0}]\subseteq E_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|T(rx)\| & \leq\|T(rx+x_{0})-Tx_{0}\|\\
 & \leq\|T(rx+x_{0})\|+\|Tx_{0}\|\\
 & \leq M+M\\
 & =2M
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\|\leq2M/r$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\|T\|\mid T\in\mathcal{A}\}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a simple application of the uniform boundedness principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of bounded linear operators 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 between Banach spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{n}x)$
\end_inset

 converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Tx:=\lim_{n\to\infty}T_{n}x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear operator.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{n}x)$
\end_inset

 is convergent we see that it must be bounded.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}=\sup_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\|T_{n}x\|<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 By the uniform boundedness principle, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\|T_{n}\|\leq M<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|Tx\| & =\|\lim_{n\to\infty}T_{n}x\|\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\|T_{n}x\|\\
 & \leq\sup_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\|T_{n}x\|\\
 & \leq\sup_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\|T_{n}\|\|x\|\\
 & \leq M\|x\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Open Mapping Theorem and Closed Graph Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Main Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be Banach spaces.
 Consider the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 with addition and scalar-multiplication defined pointwise.
 We endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 with a norm defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|(x,y)\|_{\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}}=\|x\|_{\mathcal{X}}+\|y\|_{\mathcal{Y}}.\label{eq:normbandjklfsd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y},\|\cdot\|_{\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}})$
\end_inset

 is a Banach space.
 If context is clear, then we drop 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 from the subscript in 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|_{\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}}$
\end_inset

 in order to clean notation.
 We'll use the usual projection maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}\colon\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}\to\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}\colon\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(x,y)=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(x,y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly both 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are bounded linear operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremmain}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Main result) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}\subseteq\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(\mathcal{Z})=\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is open, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(\pi_{1}^{-1}(U)\cap\mathcal{Z}))$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that by symmetry if instead of assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(\mathcal{Z})=\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(\mathcal{Z})=\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, then we have for any open set 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(\pi_{2}^{-1}(V)\cap\mathcal{Z}))$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Applications of the Main Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremmain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, let us show how to use it to prove both the open mapping theorem and the
 closed graph theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open Mapping Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Open mapping theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a surjective bounded linear operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is an open map, meaning that for any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}=\{(x,Tx)\mid x\in\mathcal{X}\}\subseteq\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace precisely because 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear operator.
 Furthemore we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(\mathcal{Z})=\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Finally, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)=\pi_{2}(\pi_{1}^{-1}(U)\cap\mathcal{Z}))$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremmain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse Mapping Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be Banach spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded linear map which is bijective.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}\colon\mathcal{Y}\to\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is also a bounded linear map.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 That 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is linear follows from basic linear algebra.
 The nontrivial part is that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also bounded.
 To see why, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be open.
 Then its preimage under 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is onto, it follows from the open mapping theorem, that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closed Graph Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a linear map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Tx_{n}\to y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Tx$
\end_inset

, or in other words, if the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,Tx)\mid x\in\mathcal{X}\}\subseteq\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 is a closed set, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Again take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}=\{(x,Tx)\mid x\in\mathcal{X}\}\subseteq\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is linear, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is closed by assumption.
 Also we clearly have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(\mathcal{Z})=\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}(V)=\pi_{1}(\pi_{2}^{-1}(V)\cap\mathcal{Z}))$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremmain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is continuous, and hence bounded.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Zabreiko's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremmain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will depend on the following lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Zabreiko) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a Banach space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon\mathcal{X}\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 be a seminorm on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
countably subadditive
\series default
, that is,
\series bold
 
\series default
suppose for every absolutely convergent series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n}\right)\leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}p(x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\leq C\|x\|$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}=\{p\leq n\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1: 
\series default
We will find an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is convex and symmetric (here symmetric means 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E_{n}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $-x\in E_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 From here it is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is convex, symmetric, and closed.
 Clearly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{X}=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}\overline{E}_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

So by the Baire category theorem, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(x_{0})\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(-x_{0})\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{1}{2}(x-x_{0})+\frac{1}{2}(x+x_{0})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x-x_{0}\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(-x_{0})\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+x_{0}\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(x_{0})\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

 is convex, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq E_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|<\rho<r$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $q>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q<1-\rho/r$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(r/\rho)x$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{qr}(y)\cap E_{N}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, so we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}(y)\cap E_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}(y)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|y_{0}-y\|<qr
\]

\end_inset

In other words, dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 give us 
\begin_inset Formula $(y-y_{0})/q\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{qr}((y-y_{0})/q)\cap E_{N}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, so we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}((y-y_{0})/q)\cap E_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Again since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}((y-y_{0})/q)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \frac{y-y_{0}-qy_{1}}{q}\right\Vert <qr
\]

\end_inset

In other words, dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $(y-y_{0}-qy_{1})/q^{2}\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq\overline{E}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{qr}((y-y_{0}-qy_{1})/q^{2})\cap E_{N}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, so we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}((y-y_{0}-qy_{1})/q^{2})\cap E_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{n}\in\mathrm{B}_{qr}\left(\frac{y-y_{0}-qy_{1}-\cdots-q^{n-1}y_{n-1}}{q^{n}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

In this case, we obtain a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})\subseteq E_{N}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|y-y_{0}-qy_{1}-q^{2}y_{2}-\cdots-q^{n}y_{n}\|<q^{n}r\label{eq:starstarmainleb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|y_{n}\|\leq r+qr$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<q<1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}q^{n}y_{n}$
\end_inset

 is absolutely convergent.
 Therefore by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:starstarmainleb})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}q^{n}y_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\backslash

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(x) & =p\left(\frac{\rho}{r}y\right)\\
 & =\frac{\rho}{r}p(y)\\
 & =\frac{\rho}{r}p\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}q^{n}y_{n}\right)\\
 & \leq\frac{\rho}{r}q^{n}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}p(y_{n})\\
 & \leq\frac{\rho}{r}q^{n}N\\
 & =\frac{\rho}{r}\frac{N}{1-q}\\
 & \leq N.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq E_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 3: 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary nonzero.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(r/2)x/\|x\|\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p((r/2)x/\|x\|)\leq N$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\leq(2N/r)\|x\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We make two remarks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Zabreiko's lemma implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|p(x_{n})-p(x)| & \leq p(x_{n}-x)\\
 & \leq C\|x_{n}-x\|\\
 & \to0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Zabreiko's lemma can be used to prove the uniform boundedness principle.
 Indeed, take 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=\sup_{T\in\mathcal{A}}\|Tx\|$
\end_inset

.
 Then it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 satisfies the properties from Zabreiko's lemma.
 Therefore there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup_{T\in\mathcal{A}}\|Tx\|\leq C\|x\|.
\]

\end_inset

Thus for any 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|Tx\|\leq C\|x\|$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\|\leq C$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof of Main Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now wish to prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremmain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon\mathcal{Y}\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 be defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(y):=\inf\{\|x\|\mid(x,y)\in\mathcal{Z}\}.
\]

\end_inset

It's easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a seminorm.
 We claim that it is also countably subadditive.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}y_{n}$
\end_inset

 be an absolutely convergent series such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}p(y_{n})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x_{n}\|<p(y_{n})+\varepsilon/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})\in\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\|x_{n}\|\leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}p(y_{n})+\varepsilon<\infty.
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is absolutely convergent.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sum_{n=1}^{N}x_{n},\sum_{n=1}^{N}y_{n})\in\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 is closed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n},\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}y_{n})\in\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}y_{n}\right) & =\inf\left\{ \|x\|\mid\left(x,\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}y_{n}\right)\in\mathcal{Z}\right\} \\
 & \leq\left\Vert \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n}\right\Vert \\
 & \leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\|x_{n}||\\
 & \leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}p(y_{n})+\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is countably subadditive.
 So we can apply Zabreiko's lemma to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 be the open unit ball in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{2}(\pi^{-1}(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)\cap\mathcal{Z})) & =\pi_{2}\{(x,y)\mid x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)\text{ and }(x,y)\in\mathcal{Z})\\
 & =\{y\in\mathcal{Y}\mid p(y)<1\}\\
 & =\{p<1\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}(\pi^{-1}(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)\cap\mathcal{Z}))$
\end_inset

 is open since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 The general case open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be easily be obtained using linearity and homogeneity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hilbert Space Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a Hilbert space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 be closed subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 We ask, is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 a closed subspace? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}=(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\perp}\cap\mathcal{L}^{\perp}=(\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L})^{\perp}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L})^{\perp}=\overline{\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}\cap\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}=\overline{\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1 implies 2, 1 implies 3, and 2 implies 4 are easy.
 It suffices to show 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=z+w$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{K}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x,y\rangle=\langle x,z+w\rangle=\langle x,z\rangle+\langle x,w\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x\perp\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}\subseteq(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}\subseteq(\mathcal{K}^{\perp})^{\perp}=\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}\subseteq(\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}=\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}\supseteq(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 are closed subspaces of a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Then there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that every 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x+y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|\leq C\|z\|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|y\|\leq C\|z\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\times\mathcal{L}\subseteq\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\times\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace of the Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence it is a Banach space itself.
 Consider the map 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{K}\times\mathcal{L}\to\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T((x,y))=x+y.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear operator.
 Furthermore, it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 By the open mapping theorem the image 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0))$
\end_inset

 must be open.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in T(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0))$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{c}(0)\subseteq T(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0))$
\end_inset

.
 This means for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\|z\|<c$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in T(\mathrm{B}_{1}(0))$
\end_inset

, that is, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x+y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|(x,y)\|=\|x\|+\|y\|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Now by scaling, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|(c/2)z/\|z\|\|<c$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(c/2)z/\|z\|=x'+y'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x'\|+\|y'\|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(2/c)\|z\|x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(2/x)\|z\|y'$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|x\|+\|y\| & <\frac{2}{c}\|z\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is closed if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It's enough to show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 with the other being a simple consequence of this one.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Using the previous proposition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}}=(\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 so it is enough to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L})^{\perp}\subseteq\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in(\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=\langle a,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a+b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is well-defined, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a'+b'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a'\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b'\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a-a'=b-b'$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $b-b'\in\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle a,y\rangle & =\langle b-b'+a',y\rangle\\
 & =\langle a',y\rangle+\langle b-b',y\rangle\\
 & =\langle a',y\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Furthermore, we claim 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 By the previous lemma, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 there exists a decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a+b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|a\|\leq C\|x\|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|b\|\leq C\|x\|$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|\ell(x)| & =|\langle a,y\rangle|\\
 & \leq\|a\|\|y\|\\
 & \leq C\|y\|\|x\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear functional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 to the whole 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 by setting
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(x)=\begin{cases}
\ell(x) & \text{ if }x\in\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}\\
0 & \text{if }x\in(\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L})^{\perp}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

This is still a bounded linear functional.
 So by the Riesz representation theorem for Hilbert spaces, there exists
 some 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(x)=\langle x,z\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y-z)+z$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(k)=\widetilde{\ell}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $y-z\in\mathcal{K}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell|_{\mathcal{L}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 then we use the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $0+x=x$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=\langle0,y\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{L}}=\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{L}}=0$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L})^{\perp}\subseteq\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The same results holds for all reflexive Banach spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ker 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 Star Equals Im 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 Perp
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propkertstarimtperp}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator.
 Then the following are true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\ker T=(\mathrm{im}\,T^{*})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\ker T^{*}=(\mathrm{im}\,T)^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(\ker T)^{\perp}=\overline{\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(\ker T^{*})^{\perp}=\overline{\mathrm{im}\,T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since identities 2-4 are simple consequences of 1, we will just prove 1
 and leave the rest as an exercise.
 Consider the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 with an inner products defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2})\rangle=\langle x_{1},x_{2}\rangle+\langle y_{1},y_{2}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=\{(x,Tx)\mid x\in\mathcal{H}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{H}\times0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 are both closed subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}=\ker T\times0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}+\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{H}\times\mathrm{im}\,T$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{\perp}=0\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{K}^{\perp} & =\{(x_{1},y_{1})\mid\langle x_{1},x\rangle+\langle y_{1},Tx\rangle=0\text{ for all }x\in\mathcal{H}\}\\
 & =\{(x_{1},y_{1})\mid\langle x_{1}+T^{*}y_{1},x\rangle=0\text{ for all }x\in\mathcal{H}\}\\
 & =\{(x_{1},y_{1})\mid x_{1}+T^{*}y_{1}=0\}\\
 & =\{(-T^{*}y_{1},y_{1})\mid y_{1}\in\mathcal{H}\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\perp}\cap\mathcal{L}^{\perp}=0\times\ker T^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp}=\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}\times\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ker T\times0 & =\mathcal{K}\cap\mathcal{L}\\
 & =(\mathcal{K}^{\perp}+\mathcal{L}^{\perp})^{\perp}\\
 & =(\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}\times\mathcal{H})^{\perp}\\
 & =(\mathrm{im}\,T^{*})^{\perp}\times0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker T=(\mathrm{im}\,T^{*})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded linear operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Uses open mapping theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Characterizing Surjectivity of a Bounded Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propkertstarimtperp})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 has dense image.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Let's state this as a theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator.
 Then the following are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T^{*}x\|\geq c\|x\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (1 implies 2) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\{x\in\mathcal{H}\mid\|T^{*}x\|\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Tz=y$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|\langle x,y\rangle| & =|\langle x,Tz\rangle|\\
 & =|\langle T^{*}x,z\rangle|\\
 & \leq\|T^{*}x\|\|z\|\\
 & \leq\|z\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is weakly bounded.
 In fact, by uniform boundedness principle, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Therefore there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|z\|\leq C$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T^{*}x\|\leq1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|\leq C$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be any arbitrary nonzero vector.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}x\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x/\|T^{*}x\|$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|T^{*}y\| & =\left\Vert T^{*}\left(\frac{x}{\|T^{*}x\|}\right)\right\Vert \\
 & =\frac{1}{\|T^{*}x\|}\|T^{*}x\|\\
 & =1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in E$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\|y\|\leq C$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|\leq C\|T^{*}x\|$
\end_inset

.
 In other words
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\|x\|\leq\|T^{*}x\|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1/C>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2 implies 3) Suppose there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T^{*}x\|\geq c\|x\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\ker T^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T^{*}x\|=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 which converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}=T^{*}x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|x_{m}-x_{n}\| & \leq\frac{1}{c}\|T^{*}(x_{m}-x_{n})\|\\
 & =\frac{1}{c}\|y_{m}-y_{n}\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus since 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is a Hilbert space, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is convergent, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is bounded/continuous, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}x=y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3 implies 1) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is closed, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T$
\end_inset

 is closed (this depends on the open mapping theorem).
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,T=\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quasi Inner-Product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a Hilbert space.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $B\colon\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is linear in the first coordinate and conjugate linear in the second coordinate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|B(x,y)|\leq C\|x\|\|y\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|B(x,x)|\geq c\|x\|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 invertible such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x,y)=\langle Tx,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently for any bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=B(x,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{y}\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{y}(x)=B(x,y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 From the properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{y}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear functional.
 Therefore by the Riesz representation theorem over Hilbert spaces, there
 exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(x,y)=\ell_{y}(x)=\langle x,z\rangle
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $S(y)=z$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear map.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\cdot,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is the usual inner-product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S=1_{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $T=S^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x,y)=\langle Tx,y\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $|B(x,y)|\leq C\|x\|\|y\|$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle Tx,y\rangle|\leq C\|x\|\|y\|$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|Tx\| & =\sup_{z\in\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]}|\langle Tx,z\rangle|\\
 & =\sup_{y\neq0}|\langle Tx,y/\|y\|\rangle|\\
 & \leq C\|x\|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\|\leq C$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, from 
\begin_inset Formula $B(y,y)\geq c\|y\|^{2}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle Ty,y\rangle\geq c\|y\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sobolev Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 be an interval.
 Recall that the space 
\begin_inset Formula $C(a,b)$
\end_inset

 is not complete with respect to the inner-product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle f,g\rangle=\int_{a}^{b}f(x)g(x)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in C(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 The completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(a,b)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle f,g\rangle_{2,1}=\langle f,g\rangle+\langle f',g'\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(C^{1}(a,b),\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle_{2,1})$
\end_inset

 is an inner-product space, but not a Hilbert space.
 Completing this space, we obtain the so called 
\series bold
Sobolev space 
\series default
which is denoted
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(a,b)$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 A concrete representation of this space can be given in the following way:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in H^{1}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\series bold
weak derivative
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is also in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(a,b)$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\series default
By weak derivative, me mean: 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 has a weak derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in L^{2}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{a}^{b}f(x)\varphi'(x)\mathrm{d}x=-\int_{a}^{b}g(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c}^{\infty}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon(a,b)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is infinitely differentiable and all its derivatives vanish as 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C^{1}(a,b)$
\end_inset

, then by integration by parts, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{a}^{b}f(x)\varphi'(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{a}^{b}f'(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x & =f(x)\varphi(x)\Big|_{a}^{b}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that the weak derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is just the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the following boundary value problem.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-y''(x)+y(x)=f(x)\text{ on }(0,1) & \text{where }f\in C(0,1)\\
y(0)=y(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sobolov Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{1}(I)=\{f\in L^{2}(I)\mid\exists g\in L^{2}(I)\mid\int_{I}f\varphi'=-\int_{I}g\varphi\text{ for all }\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(I)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We write 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=g$
\end_inset

 or the weak derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 We have inner-product
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle f,g\rangle_{H^{1}}=\int_{I}fg+\int_{I}f'g'.
\]

\end_inset

Elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

 are not always in 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}(\overline{I})$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(I)\subseteq C(\overline{I})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in H^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)-f(y)=\int_{y}^{x}f'(t)\mathrm{d}t
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\overline{I}$
\end_inset

 where we use the continuous representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the following boundary value problem.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-y''(x)+y(x)=f(x)\text{ on }(0,1) & \text{where }f\in C(0,1)\\
y(0)=y(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We say 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a classical solution if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in C^{2}[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and satisfies the boundary value problem in the classical sense (pointwise).
 Suppose we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}y'(x)\varphi'(x)+\int_{0}^{1}y(x)\varphi(x)=\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\varphi(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
weak solution
\series default
.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

 to be the subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

 consisting of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

 which vanish at the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Every classical solution is a weak solution (use integration by parts).
 The converse is in general wrong, but sometimes it is true like in our
 concrete example.
 We consider weak solutions since it is easier to prove their existence
 and uniqueness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and the linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon H_{0}^{1}(0,1)\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(\varphi)=\int_{0}^{1}\varphi(x)f(x)\mathrm{d}x.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is bounded since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|\ell(\varphi)| & =\left|\int_{0}^{1}\varphi(x)f(x)\mathrm{d}x\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{1}|\varphi(x)||f(x)|\mathrm{d}x\\
 & \leq\|\varphi\|_{2}\|f\|_{2}\\
 & \leq(\|\varphi\|_{2}+\|\varphi'\|_{2})\|f\|_{2}\\
 & =\|\varphi\|_{H^{1}}\|f\|_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the Riesz representation theorem, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\varphi)=\langle\varphi,z\rangle_{H^{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi(x)f(x)\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{1}\varphi(z)z(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}\varphi'(x)z'(x)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $y=z$
\end_inset

 is a weak solution to our problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we can show that this weak solution is actually a classical solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}y'\varphi'=-\int_{0}^{1}(y-f)\varphi
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $(y')'=y-f$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)\subseteq C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have that the weak derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in C^{1}[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and then by the same argument 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in C^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has a continuous weak derivative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable in the usual sense and its classical derivative is also
 continuous.
 The reason for this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)-g(y)=\int_{y}^{x}g'(t)\mathrm{d}t
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in I$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in H^{1}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in C(\overline{I})$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in C^{1}(\overline{I})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now it remains to show that our unique weak solution is a classical solution.
 We showed so far that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in C^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}(-y''+y-f)\varphi & =\int_{0}^{1}y'\varphi'-\int_{0}^{1}y\varphi-\int_{0}^{1}f\varphi &  & \text{integration by parts}\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $-y''+y-f=0$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere, which by continuity implies 
\begin_inset Formula $-y''+y-f=0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sturm-Liouville Boundary Value Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Sturm-Liouville boundary value problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-(p(x)y'(x))'+q(x)y(x)=f(x)\text{ on }x\in(0,1)\\
y(0)=y(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

here 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in C^{1}[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\geq\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 The weak formulation of this problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}p(x)y'(x)\varphi'(x)+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)y(x)\varphi(x)=\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\varphi(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $B\colon H_{0}^{1}(0,1)\times H_{0}^{1}(0,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(u,v)=\int_{0}^{1}p(x)u'(x)v'(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)u(x)v(x)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|B(u,v)| & \leq\int_{0}^{1}|p||u'||v'|+\int_{0}^{1}|q||u||v|\\
 & \leq C\left(\int_{0}^{1}|u'||v'|+\int_{0}^{1}|u||v|\right)\\
 & \leq C\left(\|u'\|_{2}\|v'\|_{2}+\|u\|_{2}\|v\|_{2}\right)\\
 & \leq C(\|u\|_{H^{1}}\|v\|_{H^{1}}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We also have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B(u,u) & =\int_{0}^{1}pu'u'+\int_{0}^{1}quu\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}p(x)u'(x)^{2}\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)u(x)^{2}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & \geq\int_{0}^{1}p(x)u'(x)^{2}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & \geq\alpha\int_{0}^{1}|u'(x)|^{2}\mathrm{d}x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here we need to use the Poincare inequality which says if 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|u\|_{2}\leq\|u'\|_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since if 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in H^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u(x)-u(0) & =\int_{0}^{x}u'(t)\mathrm{d}t
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Cauchy Schwarz, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|u(x)|^{2} & =\left|\int_{0}^{x}u'(t)\mathrm{d}t\right|^{2}\\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{1}|u'(t)|^{2}\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\|u'\|_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Extra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $B\colon\mathcal{H}\times\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form satisfying the same conditions as in the Lax-Milgram
 theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|B(x,y)|\leq C\|x\|\|y\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|B(y,y)|\geq c\|y\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a closed conved subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 bounded linear functional there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(x-y)\leq B(y,x-y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 If in addition 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, then this 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}B(y,y)-\ell(y)=\min_{x\in C}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}B(x,x)-\ell(x)\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=\frac{1}{2}B(x,x)-\ell(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We'll prove only the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and the leave the other part as a hard exercise.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 defines another inner-product on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 which induces the same topology as the usual one since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\|x\|\leq\sqrt{B(x,x)}\leq C\|x\|.
\]

\end_inset

We'll use the following well-known result: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is a closed convex subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(z,\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

 is attained at a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}(z)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 This point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle z-\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z,x-\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z\rangle & \leq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded linear functional.
 Then by the Riesz representation theorem there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)=B(x,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the result above we obtain that there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(z-y,x-y)\leq0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x-y) & \leq B(z,x-y)\\
 & \leq B(y,x-y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 For the last part, notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z$
\end_inset

 minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(z,\mathcal{C})=\inf\{\sqrt{B(z-x,z-x)}\mid x\in\mathcal{C}\}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G(x) & =B(z-x,z-x)\\
 & =B(z,z)-2B(z,x)+B(x,x)\\
 & =B(z,z)+2\left(\frac{1}{2}B(x,x)-B(z,x)\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\mathrm{P}_{\mathcal{C}}z$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}B(x,x)-B(z,x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the boundary value problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-(py')'+qy=f\text{ on }(0,1)\\
y(0)=\alpha\text{ and }y(1)=\beta
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{y\in H^{1}(0,1)\mid y(0)=\alpha\text{ and }y(1)=\beta\}$
\end_inset

 is used in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is no longer a subspace, but it is still closed and convex subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider as before
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(u,v)=\int_{0}^{1}p(x)u'(x)v'(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)u(x)v(x)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(u)=\int_{0}^{1}u(x)f(x)\mathrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
 We showed before that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 satisfies all the properties from Lax-Milgram theorem.
 Also we showed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon H^{1}(0,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 So we can by Stampacchia theorem to obtain a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in C$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(v-y)\leq B(y,v-y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in C$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}(v-y)f & \leq\int_{0}^{1}py'(v-y)'+\int_{0}^{1}qy(v-y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $v=y+\varphi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary element in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi f\leq\int_{0}^{1}py'\varphi'+\int_{0}^{1}qy\varphi.
\]

\end_inset

Take 
\begin_inset Formula $v=y-\varphi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary element in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi f\geq\int_{0}^{1}py'\varphi'+\int_{0}^{1}qy\varphi.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore they must be equal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}f\varphi=\int_{0}^{1}py'\varphi'+\int_{0}^{1}qy\varphi.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in C_{c}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a unique weak solution of our problem.
 To show that this 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a unique classical solution is exactly the same as before.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fredhold Alternative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T\text{ is onto} & \iff T^{*}\text{ is injective with closed range}\\
 & \iff T^{*}\text{ is bounded below}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in C([0,1]\times[0,1])$
\end_inset

 and consider the integral equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y(x)+\int_{0}^{1}K(x,t)y(t)\mathrm{d}t=f(x)\label{eq:fredholmequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are given.
 We want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The following alternative holds: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Either 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:fredholmequation})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Or 
\begin_inset Formula $y(x)+\int_{0}^{1}K(t,x)y(t)\mathrm{d}t=0$
\end_inset

 has a non-trivial solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon L^{2}(0,1)\to L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 the integral operator defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(Tg)(x)=\int_{0}^{1}K(x,t)g(t)\mathrm{d}t
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 It's not hard to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a bounded operator whenever
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}|K(x,t)|^{2}\mathrm{d}x\mathrm{d}t<\infty.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is also a compact operator.
 With this operator, we can restate the Fredholm alternative as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Either 
\begin_inset Formula $1+T$
\end_inset

 is surjetive, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $y+Ty=f$
\end_inset

 has a solution for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
or 
\begin_inset Formula $1+T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is not injective, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $y+T^{*}y=0$
\end_inset

 has a non-trivial solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 1 says 
\begin_inset Formula $1+T$
\end_inset

 is surjective and 2 says 
\begin_inset Formula $1+T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact operator.
 Then exactly one of the following statements must be true:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+T)x=b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there exists nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+T^{*})x=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The crucial ingredient in the proof is the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is a compact operator, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}(1+T)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}(1+T)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\to y$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathrm{im}(1+T)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}=(1+T)x_{n}$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\mathrm{d}(x_{n},\ker(1+T))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}=\mathrm{P}_{\ker(1+T)}x_{n}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\|x_{n}-z_{n}\|$
\end_inset

.
 Observe
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{n} & =x_{n}+Tx_{n}\\
 & =x_{n}+Tx_{n}-(1+T)z_{n}\\
 & =(x_{n}-z_{n})+T(x_{n}-z_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We'll now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\|x_{n}-z_{n}\|$
\end_inset

 is a bounded sequence.
 Suppose not.
 Then there exists a subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}\|\to\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{k}=\frac{x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}}{\|x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}\|}.
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{k}+Tw_{k} & =\frac{x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}+T(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})}{\|x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}\|}\\
 & =\frac{y_{n_{k}}}{\|x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}}\|}\\
 & \to0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{k})$
\end_inset

 is a bounded sequence and since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is compact we have that there exists a subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{k_{i}})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Tw_{k_{i}})$
\end_inset

 is convergent.
 But we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{k}+Tw_{k}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{k_{i}})$
\end_inset

 is convergent since it is a difference of convergent sequences.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\lim_{i\to\infty}w_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1+T)a & =a+Ta\\
 & =\lim_{i\to\infty}w_{k_{i}}+T(\lim_{i\to\infty}w_{k_{i}})\\
 & =\lim_{i\to\infty}w_{k_{i}}+\lim_{i\to\infty}Tw_{k_{i}}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\ker(1+T)$
\end_inset

.
 However this is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(w_{k},\ker(1+T))=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(w_{k},\ker(1+T))\leq\|w_{k}-a\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $(\|x_{n}-z_{n}\|)$
\end_inset

 must be bounded.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

 is convergent since it is the difference of two convergent sequences.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\lim_{k\to\infty}(x_{n_{k}}-z_{n_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u=y-Tu$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(1+T)u$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fredholm alternative follows from this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Farkas' Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

(Farkas' Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then exactly one of the following is true:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 is solvable and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq0$
\end_inset

 (all coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are non-negative);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\top}y\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b,y\rangle<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generalization of Farkas' Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a closed convex conse in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{*}=\{z\in\mathcal{H}\mid\langle x,z\rangle\geq0\text{ for all }x\in C\}
\]

\end_inset

be the 
\series bold
dual cone 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded linear operator.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A(C)=\{Ax\mid x\in C\}
\]

\end_inset

is closed, then exactly one of the following is true:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}y\in C^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b,y\rangle<0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell_{y}(A(C))\geq0 & \iff\ell_{y}(Ax)\geq0\text{ for all }x\in C\\
 & \iff\langle Ax,y\rangle\geq0\text{ for all }x\in C\\
 & \iff\langle x,A^{*}y\rangle\geq0\text{ for all }x\in C\\
 & \iff A^{*}y\in C^{*}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the second condition is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{y}(A(C))\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 So the general form of Farka's lemma is a direct consequence of the 2nd
 geometric form of Hahn-Banach applied in the following way: if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin A(C)$
\end_inset

, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A(C)$
\end_inset

 is a closed convex set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b\}$
\end_inset

 is a closed convex and compact set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(C)\cap\{b\}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $A(C)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b\}$
\end_inset

 can be strictly separated by a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\{b\})<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(A(C))\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to condition 2 by the Riesz representation theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{*}=0$
\end_inset

, so Farkas' lemma reduces to the statement
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{im}\,A=(\ker A^{*})^{\perp},
\]

\end_inset

whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,A$
\end_inset

 i s closed.
 We use Fenchel-Rockafellar to get a quantitative form of Farkas' lemma.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\|x-b\|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\mathrm{I}_{C}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then Fenchel-Rockafellar implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{x\in\mathcal{H}}(\varphi(Ax)+\psi(x))=\sup_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(-\varphi^{*}(-y)-\psi^{*}(A^{*}y))=\max_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(-\varphi^{*}(-y)-\psi^{*}(A^{*}y)).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\inf_{x\in\mathcal{H}}(\|Ax-b\|+\mathrm{I}_{C}(x)) & =\sup_{\substack{y\in\mathcal{H}\\
\|y\|\leq1
}
}(\langle y,b\rangle-\mathrm{q}_{C}(A^{*}y)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(b,A(C)) & =\inf_{x\in C}\|Ax-b\|=\sup_{\substack{y\in\mathcal{H}\\
\|y\|\leq1
}
}(\langle-y,b\rangle-\mathrm{q}_{C}(A^{*}(-y)))
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(b,A(C))=\sup_{\substack{y\in\mathcal{H}\\
\|y\|\leq1\\
A^{*}y\in C^{*}
}
}(-\langle y,b\rangle).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Another Application of Fenchel Rockafellar to Conic/Linear Programming
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a closed convex cone.
 We want to show
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{Ax-b\in C}\langle c,x\rangle=\sup_{\substack{A^{*}y=c\\
y\in C^{*}
}
}\langle b,y\rangle
\]

\end_inset

Fenchel Rockafellar gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{x\in\mathcal{H}}(\varphi(Ax)+\psi(x))=\sup_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(-\varphi^{*}(-y)-\psi^{*}(A^{*}y))
\]

\end_inset

If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(Ax)=\mathrm{I}_{C+b}(Ax)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\langle c,x\rangle$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\inf_{Ax-b\in C}\langle c,x\rangle & =\inf_{x\in\mathcal{H}}(\mathrm{I}_{C+b}(Ax)+\langle c,x\rangle)\\
 & =\sup_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(-\mathrm{q}_{C+b}(-y)-\mathrm{I}_{\{c\}}(A^{*}y))\\
 & =\sup_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(-\mathrm{q}_{C}(-y)-\mathrm{q}_{\{b\}}(-y)-\mathrm{I}_{\{c\}}(A^{*}y))\\
 & =\sup_{y\in\mathcal{H}}(\mathrm{I}_{C^{*}}(y)+\langle y,b\rangle-\mathrm{I}_{\{c\}}(A^{*}y))\\
 & =\sup_{\substack{A^{*}y=c\\
y\in C^{*}
}
}\langle y,b\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectral Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From now on we work with Hilbert spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following boundary value problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-(py')'+qy=f\\
y(0)=y(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Solution operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S\colon L^{2}(0,1)\to L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Sf$
\end_inset

 is the unique weak solution of the BVP above.
 We proved that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is linear, bounded, compact.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint.
 We know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}p(x)(Sf(x))'\varphi'(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)Sf(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x.
\]

\end_inset

Also
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}p(x)(Sg(x))'\varphi'(x)\mathrm{d}x+\int_{0}^{1}q(x)Sg(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{1}g(x)\varphi(x)\mathrm{d}x.
\]

\end_inset

Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=Sg$
\end_inset

 in the first and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=Sf$
\end_inset

 in the second one we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}f(x)Sg(x)\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{1}g(x)Sf(x)\mathrm{d}x.
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,Sg\rangle_{2}=\langle Sf,g\rangle_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a compact self-adjoint operator and we can apply to it the spectral
 theorem.
 Thus there exists an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Se_{n}=\mu_{n}e_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Sf=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu_{n}\langle f,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=1/\mu_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-(p(x)(Se_{n})'(x))'+q(x)Se_{n}(x)=e_{n}(x) & \text{for all }x\in(0,1)\\
Se_{n}(0)=Se_{n}(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
-(pe_{n}')'+qe_{n}=\lambda_{n}e_{n} & \text{for all }x\in(0,1)\\
e_{n}(0)=e_{1}(1)=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $Sf\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{n}e_{n}=Se_{n}\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}\in H_{0}^{1}(0,1)\subseteq C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore each 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}$
\end_inset

 is also a classical solution of the BVP above for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}\in C^{2}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spectral Theorem for Bounded Self-Adjoint Operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator.
 The 
\series bold
spectrum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(T)=\{\lambda\in\mathbb{C}\mid\lambda-T\text{ is not invertible}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda-T$
\end_inset

 is not invertible is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(\lambda-T)\neq0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,(\lambda-T)\neq\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is finite-dimensional, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(\lambda-T)\neq0$
\end_inset

 ie equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,(\lambda-T)\neq\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 However in the infinite-dimensional case, this need not hold.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(\lambda-T)\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 So the spectrum contains all eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator.
 The 
\series bold
resolvent set 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(T)=\mathbb{C}\backslash\sigma(T).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator with 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1-T$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the series 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}T^{n}=1+T+T^{2}+\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

It's partial sums forms a Cauchy sequence and hence must be convergent.
 Thus the series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}T^{n}$
\end_inset

 is convergent.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq2$
\end_inset

, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(1-T)(1+T+T^{2}+\cdots+T^{N-1})=1-T^{N}.\label{eq:Ntoinfdjflksd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T^{N}\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{N}\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus taking 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:Ntoinfdjflksd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-T)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}T^{n}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $1-T$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded operator.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(T)\subseteq\{z\in\mathbb{C}\mid|z|\leq\|T\|\}$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(T)$
\end_inset

 is compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
